50–Female":"1450–Deceased","1478–1553":"1478–1553","1450–Male":"1450–Deceased","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1553":"1553","1450":"1450","1549":"1549","Northall, Dunstable, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northall, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Hatfield, Herefordshire, England":"Hatfield, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Sergio, Alicia, Carolina, Enrique, Felipe, Javier, Jorge, Manuel, Mario, Miguel.  French Michel, Camille.","French: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Médéric</i>, derived from an ancient Germanic personal name composed of <i>mecht</i> ‘strength, might’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power; ruler’.","French: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Aimery</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Haimeric</i>, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīk</i> ‘realm, power’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lemerise","meanings":["French Canadian: from the female personal name <i>Émerise</i>, a derivative of the male name <i>Aimery</i> (see   Mery  ), with fused definite article <i>l'</i>."]},{"name":"Merry","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>merie</i>, <i>mirie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ (Old English <i>myrge</i>). Compare   Merriman  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mearadhaigh</b>, <b>Ó Meardha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mearadhach</i>, a descendant of <i>Meardha</i>’, personal names derived from an adjective meaning ‘lively, wild, or high-spirited’. Where Irish <i>dh</i> has been Anglicized as <i>g</i>, there is possible confusion with   Merrick  .","French: variant of   Mery   1."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":99,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":108,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Mery was born in 1450, in Hatfield, Herefordshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Young."},"et":{"1450–":"1450–Surnud","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1478–1553":"1478–1553","1450–Male":"1450–S